7d7fe10e-080b-4de0-b498-9d0f2e6c02e2.0ef9da31-414b-4a1b-a16b-c6ab503220c8.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.

7d7fe10e-080b-4de0-b498-9d0f2e6c02e2.56dd81e6-bd59-4cf7-9267-d571ae33b6df.description=
Checks if a number or word is equal to another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 \=\= value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

7d7fe10e-080b-4de0-b498-9d0f2e6c02e2.fdf7f2c9-2f64-49a5-ac32-579ba8e79294.description=
Converts a XML document to a JSON array or a JSON object.

Inputs\:
    xml - The XML document (in the form of a String).
    textElementsName - specify custom property name for text elements. This will be used for elements that have attributes and text content.
Default value\: _text
    includeRootElement - The flag for including the xml root in the resulted JSON.
Default value\: true
    includeAttributes - The flag for including XML attributes in the resulted JSON (
Default value\: true
    prettyPrint - The flag for formatting the resulted XML.
Default value\: true
    parsingFeatures - The list of XML parsing features separated by new line (CRLF). The feature name - value must be separated by empty space. Setting specific features this field could be used to avoid XML security issues like "XML Entity Expansion injection" and "XML External Entity injection". To avoid aforementioned security issues we strongly recommend to set this input to the following values\: 
http\://apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl true 
http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities false 
http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities false 
When the "http\://apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl" feature is set to "true" the parser will throw a FATAL ERROR if the incoming document contains a DOCTYPE declaration.  
When the "http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities" feature is set to "false" the parser will not include external general entities. 
When the "http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities" feature is set to "false" the parser will not include external parameter entities or the external DTD subset. 
If any of the validations fails, the operation will fail with an error message describing the problem. 
Default value\:
http\://apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl true
http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities false
http\://xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. The resulted JSON Document or JSON objects in form of a String.
    returnCode - 0 for success; -1 for failure.
    namespacesPrefixes - The list of tag prefixes separated by delimiter.
    namespacesUris - The corresponding list of namespaces Uris separated by delimiter. (They can be used as input for Convert JSON to XML Operation)
	
Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Examples\:
1. xml\=
  John
  100
  true  
 and the other values with their default values you will get

returnResult\={
  "root"\: {
    "name"\: "John",
    "age"\: "100",
    "retired"\: "true"
  }
}
namespacesPrefixes \=
namespacesUris \=
returnCode\: 0

2. xml \= 
12

value1
value2



size1010
colorblue


 and the other values with their default values you will get

returnResult \=
{
  "root"\: {
    "@id"\: "Page1",
    "ui\:position"\: {
      "x"\: "1",
      "y"\: "2"
    },
    "f\:properties"\: {
      "f\:property"\: [
        { "key1"\: "value1" },
        { "key2"\: "value2" }
      ]
    },
    "details"\: {
      "item"\: [
        {
          "@id"\: "1",
          "type"\: "size",
          "height"\: "10",
          "width"\: "10"
        },
        {
          "@id"\: "2",
          "type"\: "color",
          "name"\: "blue"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
namespacesPrefixes \= f,ui
namespacesUris \= http\://java.sun.com/jsf/core,urn\:x-hp\:2012\:software\:eve\:uibinding
returnCode\: 0

3. 
xml \= Apples
textElementsName\=_text

returnResult \= 
{
  "td"\: {
    "@id"\: "1",
    "_text"\: "Apples"
}

Notes\:
1. The XML document must be well formed.
2. The xml's attributes are prefixed with '@' in the resulted JSON.
3. The textElementsName will be used when an element from the xml input has attribute and text.
